Requirement

velotytoRNA velocity RNA velocity analysis of single-cell data was performed using velotyto

https://doi.org/10.1172/jci.insight.131092 fromhttps://doi.org/10.1172/jci.insight.131092

Figure 3. Transcriptional activity in aging cardiac fibroblasts. (D) Transcriptional activity was estimated by measuring the ratio between unspliced and spliced mRNAs. This so-called RNA velocity is represented by high-dimensional vectors; the longer the arrow in the plot, the higher the transcriptional activity as seen in the extremities of states h, j, and l plot containing mostly old cells.

Application Scenarios

RNA velocityRNARNARNAmRNARNARNA RNA velocity, the time derivative of RNA abundance, can be predicted and estimated by distinguishing between unspliced and spliced mrnas in standard single-cell RNA sequencing. Researchers believe that the RNA rate is a vector that can predict the state of a single cell in the coming hours. The RNA rate will greatly assist researchers in analyzing developmental lineages and cell dynamics.

Make reference

cellrangermm10reference The cellranger official website has a reference for the well-made mm10, but the author did not directly adopt it.

Reads were aligned to GRCm38 reference genome, and gene annotation was extracted from gencode vM12. Intronic mapped reads were assumed to be part of pre-mRNAs; therefore, they were also assigned to the respective gene. Because Cell Ranger counts only those reads that map to exons, we created a modifed gene transfer format file, which denotes each gene transcript locus as 1 exon and rebuilt a Cell Ranger reference (cellranger mkref). This step was necessary because of a high number of pre-mRNA in nuclei.

GRCm38gencode vM12 The author USES a genome sequence GRCm38, Gene annotation is gencode vM12

single-nucleus sequencingintroncountsGFT1exon In this paper, single-nucleus sequencing was adopted. To include the counts in the intron region in the expression as well, the authors remade the gene GFT file. View the entire transcript as one exon.

10X Regarding this point, the 10X official website states as follows:

To be considered for transcriptome alignment, genes must have annotations with feature type exon (column 3) in the GTF file.

gencode vM128transcriptexon The following are the first 8 columns of gencode vM12. We need to extract all the transcripts and then change them to exon

chr1    HAVANA  gene    3073253 3074322 .   +   .
chr1    HAVANA  transcript  3073253 3074322 .   +   .
chr1    HAVANA  exon    3073253 3074322 .   +   .
chr1    ENSEMBL gene    3102016 3102125 .   +   .
chr1    ENSEMBL transcript  3102016 3102125 .   +   .

python Solve this problem with a simple python script.

with open("gencode.vM12.annotation.gtf") as fi:
    with open("gencode.vM12.transcripts.gtf", "w") as fo:
        for line in fi:
            if line.startswith("#"):
                fo.write(line)
            elif line.split()[2] == "transcript":
                line_list = line.rstrip("\n").split("\t")
                line_list[2] = "exon"
                fo.write("\t".join(line_list)+"\n")
            else:
                pass

build index Now lets build the index

cellranger mkref --genome="gencode_vM12" \
                 --fasta=GRCm38.p5.genome.fa \
                 --genes=gencode.vM12.transcripts.gtf \
                 --nthreads 8

32GB8threads1 This step requires approximately 32GB of memory. Set it to 8 threads, it will take approximately 1 hour.

Indexing a typical human 3Gb FASTA file often takes up to 8 core hours and requires 32 GB of memory.

cellranger fastq Regarding the naming rules for cellranger fastq files:

[Sample Name] [Sample Index] [Lane ID] [Read Type]

For example:

Y3_SaS_CB_004_S5_L006_R1_001.fastq.gz
Sample Name = Y3_SaS_CB_004
Sample Index = S5
Lane ID = L006
Read Type = R1

cellranger count Take this sample as an example. The command for cellranger count is as follows:

# data/
# Under the data/ folder
cellranger count --id=young3 \
--transcriptome=../ref/gencode_vM12 \
--fastqs=fastq/Y3/ \
--sample=Y3_SaS_CB_004 \ # fastqSampleNamecellranger  # Note that this must be the SampleName prefix of the fastq file. 
--localcores=16 \ # 16   # assigns 16 cores
--expect-cells=10000 \ 
--localmem=64 # 64G  # assigns 64G of memory

Conclusion

The result graph differs somewhat from the article. The analysis suggests that the reasons might be due to differences in the number of cells and the selection of characteristic genes. However, the conclusion of the article holds true.
